"nudge_anger_notification_43" = "Put your hands behind your back. Unclench.";
"nudge_anger_notification_44" = "Is this your ego or your values talking?";
"nudge_anger_notification_45" = "Let it go. It's not worth carrying.";
"nudge_anger_notification_46" = "Silence is louder than shouting.";
"nudge_anger_notification_47" = "Name the emotion. Naming calms it.";
"nudge_anger_notification_48" = "Physical anger? Use physical release. Run.";
"nudge_anger_notification_49" = "You can be angry without being destructive.";
"nudge_anger_notification_50" = "The moment you pause, you've already won.";
"nudge_anger_notification_51" = "Release the jaw. Drop the shoulders.";
"nudge_anger_notification_52" = "Not every battle needs a warrior.";
"nudge_anger_notification_53" = "Breathe like the ocean: slow, rhythmic, deep.";
"nudge_anger_notification_54" = "Channel anger into something constructive.";
"nudge_anger_notification_55" = "Forgiveness isn't for them. It's for you.";
"nudge_anger_notification_56" = "What would your wisest self do right now?";
"nudge_anger_notification_57" = "Hold an ice cube. Feel the anger melt.";
"nudge_anger_notification_58" = "Anger clouds judgment. Wait for clarity.";
"nudge_anger_notification_59" = "One calm breath can change everything.";
"nudge_anger_notification_60" = "You are not your anger.";
"nudge_anger_detail_15" = "Between stimulus and response, there is a space. In that space is your freedom. Pause for 5 seconds before reacting. Those 5 seconds change everything.";
"nudge_anger_detail_16" = "Anger is almost always a secondary emotion—underneath it is hurt, fear, frustration, or feeling disrespected. Find the primary emotion. Address that instead.";
"nudge_anger_detail_17" = "Ten slow, deep breaths. In through your nose, out through your mouth. Your heart rate will drop, your vision will clear, and your decisions will improve.";
"nudge_anger_detail_18" = "You can't control what others do. But your response is 100% yours. Own it. A measured response shows strength. An explosive reaction shows loss of control.";
"nudge_anger_detail_19" = "Zoom out: In 5 years, will this moment matter? In 5 months? In 5 weeks? Most anger is about things that are genuinely temporary. Don't give them permanent power.";
"nudge_anger_detail_20" = "Holding onto anger is like gripping a hot coal—you're the one getting burned. The other person often doesn't even know you're angry. Release it.";
"nudge_anger_detail_21" = "Words said in anger can never be taken back. Relationships damaged in rage can take years to repair. Leave the room. Write it down. Come back later.";
"nudge_anger_detail_22" = "Anger triggers adrenaline and cortisol, raising your blood pressure and heart rate. Take three deep breaths. Each exhale physically lowers your blood pressure.";
"nudge_anger_detail_23" = "Reacting is instinct. Responding is wisdom. The difference is a pause. Before you speak or act, insert a pause. Even 3 seconds changes the outcome.";
"nudge_anger_detail_24" = "No matter what happens to you, your response is yours. Nobody 'makes' you angry—you choose anger as a response. You can also choose differently.";
"nudge_anger_detail_25" = "Physical distance creates emotional distance. Leave the room, go outside, walk around the block. When you return, you'll see the situation more clearly.";
"nudge_anger_detail_26" = "Count to 10 slowly. Say each number in your mind. Focus on the counting, not the anger. By 10, your amygdala will have calmed and your cortex can think.";
"nudge_anger_detail_27" = "Feeling angry is human and valid. Yelling, hitting, or saying cruel things is a choice—and not the only one. Feel the anger. Choose a different expression.";
"nudge_anger_detail_28" = "Clench both fists as hard as you can for 5 seconds. Now release. Feel the tension drain. Progressive relaxation works. Your body can override your mind.";
"nudge_anger_detail_29" = "What would actually help you right now? Not revenge, not being right. What would bring you peace? A walk? Music? A conversation? Go do that instead.";
"nudge_anger_detail_30" = "Other people's behavior is a reflection of their inner state, not your worth. You don't have to absorb their negativity. Let it pass through you.";
"nudge_anger_detail_31" = "People in pain often cause pain. The person who angered you might be carrying something heavy. That doesn't excuse their behavior, but it explains it. Don't add to the cycle.";
"nudge_anger_detail_32" = "Ask yourself: Do I want to be right, or do I want to be at peace? Being right feels good for a moment. Peace lasts. Choose the lasting one.";
"nudge_anger_detail_33" = "Breathe out the anger: exhale slowly for 8 counts. Inhale calm: breathe in slowly for 4 counts. Repeat until your body temperature drops and your mind clears.";
"nudge_anger_detail_34" = "Sending that text, making that call, posting that comment—all permanent actions based on a temporary emotion. Wait 24 hours. If you still feel the same, act then.";
"nudge_anger_detail_35" = "Anger feels powerful, but it's actually a loss of control. True power is the ability to feel intense emotion and still choose a measured response. That's strength.";
"nudge_anger_detail_36" = "Speaking softly when angry is a power move. It forces the other person to lean in, listen, and engage differently. Lower your voice. Watch the dynamic shift.";
"nudge_anger_detail_37" = "Under the anger, there's a need. Respect? Safety? Fairness? Understanding? Name the need. Communicate the need. That's more effective than expressing the anger.";
"nudge_anger_detail_38" = "Anger feeds on attention. The more you think about it, the bigger it gets. Starve it by redirecting your attention to something else for 15 minutes.";
"nudge_anger_detail_39" = "Cold water on your face activates the dive reflex, immediately slowing your heart rate and calming your nervous system. It's the fastest physical anger reset.";
"nudge_anger_detail_40" = "Not every provocation deserves engagement. Some battles aren't worth fighting. Choose the ones that matter and walk away from the ones that don't.";
"nudge_anger_detail_41" = "A calm response in a heated moment earns more respect than any display of anger. It shows mastery over yourself. That's the most impressive thing you can show.";
"nudge_anger_detail_42" = "Think about the last time you said something in anger. How did it feel afterward? Regret, right? Save yourself that regret. Stay quiet until you're calm.";
"nudge_anger_detail_43" = "Put your hands behind your back or in your pockets. Open your palms. This open posture sends a signal to your brain that you're not in danger.";
"nudge_anger_detail_44" = "Is your ego wounded, or are your values violated? Ego wounds heal with perspective. Value violations require assertive, calm communication—not rage.";
"nudge_anger_detail_45" = "Carrying anger is carrying a weight that only you feel. The person you're angry at has moved on. Put the weight down. It's not yours to carry.";
"nudge_anger_detail_46" = "Sometimes the most powerful thing you can say is nothing. Silence in the face of provocation is louder than any argument. Try it.";
"nudge_anger_detail_47" = "Say: 'I'm feeling angry right now.' Naming the emotion reduces amygdala activation by up to 50%. It's neuroscience. Label the feeling, weaken it.";
"nudge_anger_detail_48" = "Physical anger needs physical release—not on a person. Run, hit a pillow, do burpees. Get the adrenaline out of your system through exertion, not aggression.";
"nudge_anger_detail_49" = "You can be angry without being destructive. Anger is information—it tells you something matters. Use it as fuel for change, not for damage.";
"nudge_anger_detail_50" = "The moment you pause instead of reacting, you've already won the most important battle—the one against your own impulse. That pause is your superpower.";
"nudge_anger_detail_51" = "Body scan: Unclench your jaw. Lower your shoulders. Open your fists. Soften your brow. Your body and emotions are connected. Relax the body, calm the mind.";
"nudge_anger_detail_52" = "Ask yourself: Is this my battle, or am I fighting someone else's? Not everything requires your intervention. Sometimes the wisest move is to let it go.";
"nudge_anger_detail_53" = "Breathe like the ocean: slow inhale like a wave coming in, slow exhale like a wave going out. Rhythm calms the nervous system. Be the ocean, not the storm.";
"nudge_anger_detail_54" = "Anger is energy. Destructive anger destroys things you care about. Constructive anger builds change. Channel the energy into solving the problem, not amplifying it.";
"nudge_anger_detail_55" = "Forgiveness doesn't mean what they did was okay. It means you're freeing yourself from carrying the weight. Forgiveness is the ultimate act of self-care.";
"nudge_anger_detail_56" = "Your wisest self isn't angry right now. They're observing, understanding, and choosing with intention. Step into that version of yourself. They know what to do.";
"nudge_anger_detail_57" = "Hold an ice cube in your fist. Focus on the intense cold sensation. The physical discomfort redirects your brain from emotional pain to physical sensation.";
"nudge_anger_detail_58" = "Anger narrows your vision—literally. You see fewer options, fewer perspectives, fewer solutions. Wait for the anger to pass and your field of view expands.";
"nudge_anger_detail_59" = "One calm breath—4 seconds in, 4 seconds out—activates your prefrontal cortex and quiets your amygdala. That single breath can change the entire trajectory of this moment.";
"nudge_anger_detail_60" = "Anger visits you, but it is not you. You are the awareness behind the anger—the one who notices it, feels it, and chooses what to do with it. You are bigger.";

// MARK: - Nudge Expansion v1.8.0 — obsessive (15-60)
"nudge_obsessive_notification_15" = "Good enough is good enough.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_16" = "Step back. Gain perspective.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_17" = "Checking again won't change anything.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_18" = "Let it be imperfect.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_19" = "You've done enough. Move on.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_20" = "The detail doesn't matter as much as you think.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_21" = "Perfection is the enemy of done.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_22" = "Walk away from it for 15 minutes.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_23" = "You're overthinking this.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_24" = "It's done. Let it go.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_25" = "Checking once is enough.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_26" = "Your anxiety is driving, not your logic.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_27" = "The compulsion is the problem, not the thing.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_28" = "Sit with the discomfort. It fades.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_29" = "You don't need to control everything.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_30" = "Breathe. Release the need for certainty.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_31" = "80% done is still done.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_32" = "Stop editing. Start living.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_33" = "Uncertainty is okay. Really.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_34" = "The loop is the problem, not the thought.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_35" = "Lock the door once. Trust yourself.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_36" = "You checked already. Remember that.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_37" = "Not everything needs to be perfect.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_38" = "Your time is more valuable than another check.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_39" = "Accept 'good enough' as a victory.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_40" = "The compulsion doesn't keep you safe.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_41" = "Delay the urge by 5 minutes.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_42" = "What would happen if you just... didn't?";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_43" = "You can handle the uncertainty.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_44" = "Put it down. Walk away.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_45" = "Productivity doesn't require perfection.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_46" = "The ritual doesn't protect you.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_47" = "Ship it. Learn from feedback.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_48" = "You're spending time, not improving quality.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_49" = "Trust the first check.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_50" = "Progress requires releasing control.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_51" = "Messy is human. Human is beautiful.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_52" = "One more pass won't change anything.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_53" = "Done > perfect. Always.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_54" = "Your brain is stuck. Unstick it.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_55" = "Go outside. Reset the loop.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_56" = "The world won't end if it's not perfect.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_57" = "Invest that energy somewhere new.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_58" = "Let go. Seriously. Let go.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_59" = "Imperfection is freedom.";
"nudge_obsessive_notification_60" = "You've done your best. That's enough.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_15" = "Perfection is an illusion—there's always one more adjustment, one more check, one more revision. But 'good enough' is real and it's done. Accept good enough.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_16" = "When you're too close to something, you lose perspective. Step away for 15 minutes. When you return, you'll see it with fresh eyes. Distance creates clarity.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_17" = "Checking again gives temporary relief but strengthens the compulsion long-term. Each check teaches your brain that checking is necessary. Break the cycle. Don't check.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_18" = "Imperfect work that exists is infinitely more valuable than perfect work that doesn't. Let the imperfections stay. They're proof of progress, not evidence of failure.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_19" = "You've invested enough time and attention. Additional effort yields diminishing returns—each pass catches less while costing the same. Stop. Move on to something new.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_20" = "The detail you're obsessing over? Most people won't notice it. And those who do won't care. Your standard is higher than the world requires. Lower it to human.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_21" = "Perfection prevents completion. Every masterpiece has imperfections visible to the creator but invisible to the audience. Ship it. Nobody expects perfection but you.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_22" = "Set a timer for 15 minutes and walk away from whatever you're working on. Don't check it. Don't think about it. When you return, the urge will have diminished.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_23" = "You've thought about this enough. More thinking won't improve the outcome—it'll just delay it. The decision is made. The work is done. Trust yourself.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_24" = "Say out loud: 'It's done.' Repeat it. The verbal declaration sends a signal to your brain that the task is complete. Now physically move to something else.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_25" = "One check is information. Multiple checks are anxiety. You already have the information you need. The additional checks are your anxiety talking, not your logic.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_26" = "Your logical brain knows it's fine. Your anxious brain says check again. Recognize which one is driving right now. Choose to listen to logic, not anxiety.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_27" = "The compulsive behavior isn't solving a real problem—it's trying to reduce anxiety. But it actually feeds the anxiety. The real solution is to sit with the discomfort.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_28" = "Sit with the uncomfortable feeling of not checking, not fixing, not perfecting. The discomfort peaks in about 15 minutes and then fades. You can handle 15 minutes.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_29" = "You cannot control every outcome. Accepting this isn't weakness—it's wisdom. Focus on what you can influence, release what you can't. That's real power.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_30" = "Breathe deeply. Uncertainty is the natural state of life. Seeking certainty through compulsive behavior doesn't create certainty—it creates exhaustion. Breathe and let go.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_31" = "The 80/20 rule: 80% of results come from 20% of effort. You've done the 20%. The remaining effort yields almost nothing. Redirect your energy to something new.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_32" = "Stop editing your email for the 5th time. Stop rearranging things that are already arranged. Stop perfecting what's already good. Go live your life instead.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_33" = "Certainty is a fantasy. Even checking 100 times won't guarantee the outcome. Learn to tolerate 'probably fine.' Because probably fine is actually fine.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_34" = "The intrusive thought isn't the problem—everyone has random thoughts. The problem is engaging with it, analyzing it, and trying to neutralize it. Just let it pass.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_35" = "You locked the door. You know you did. The doubt isn't a memory problem—it's an anxiety problem. Trust the action. Walk away.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_36" = "Say to yourself: 'I checked already and it was fine.' Repeat it as a fact, because it is one. Your memory is reliable. Your anxiety is not.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_37" = "The world is beautifully imperfect. Relationships, nature, art—all contain imperfections that make them real. Your work doesn't need to be the exception.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_38" = "Calculate: 10 minutes of extra checking × 5 times a day × 365 days = 30 hours per year. That's more than a full work week spent on anxiety rituals. Reclaim your time.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_39" = "'Good enough' isn't settling—it's strategic. It means recognizing when further effort produces negligible improvement. Celebrate 'good enough' as a smart decision.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_40" = "The compulsion promises safety: 'Check one more time and you'll feel secure.' It never delivers. You check, feel brief relief, then need to check again. It's a trap.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_41" = "When the urge to check or fix arises, set a 5-minute delay. Don't fight the urge—just postpone it. After 5 minutes, the urge is usually weaker or gone.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_42" = "What's the actual worst case if you don't check, don't fix, don't perfect? Usually, nothing bad happens. And you've saved time and mental energy. Test it.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_43" = "Uncertainty feels threatening, but you handle it every day. You cross streets, eat food, trust people—all uncertain. You can handle this uncertainty too.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_44" = "Physically put it down. Close the laptop, put down the phone, walk away from the desk. Physical separation from the task breaks the obsessive loop.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_45" = "Productivity isn't about perfecting one thing—it's about completing many things well enough. Redistribute the energy you're spending on perfection.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_46" = "Rituals and compulsions don't prevent bad outcomes—they prevent you from learning that bad outcomes rarely happen. Each time you resist, you learn you're safe.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_47" = "Ship the imperfect version and learn from real feedback. Imagined criticism is always worse than real criticism. And real feedback actually helps you improve.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_48" = "You're investing time without improving quality. There's a point of diminishing returns, and you passed it a while ago. Recognize it and redirect.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_49" = "Trust the first check. Your first check was thorough and accurate. Subsequent checks are anxiety, not quality control. Trust your competence.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_50" = "Growth requires releasing control of the outcome. You can control your effort, not the result. Let go of the result. Focus on the process.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_51" = "Messy, imperfect, and real is more beautiful than polished, controlled, and exhausting. Embrace the mess. That's where life actually happens.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_52" = "One more pass through the document, one more check of the stove, one more look at the email—none of these will change the outcome. But they'll steal your time.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_53" = "Done is better than perfect. This isn't laziness—it's efficiency. The most successful people ship imperfect work and iterate. Join them.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_54" = "Your brain is stuck in a loop—thought, anxiety, compulsion, brief relief, repeat. Recognize the loop. Name it: 'That's the loop again.' Naming breaks it.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_55" = "Go outside. Look at the sky. Feel the air. Nature doesn't obsess over details—leaves are asymmetrical, clouds are uneven, and it's all beautiful. Let that teach you.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_56" = "The world has survived billions of years of imperfection. Your imperfect email, your unlevel shelf, your asymmetrical garden—the world won't notice. Let it go.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_57" = "The energy you're spending on this one thing could fuel three other projects. It's not just time you're losing—it's opportunity. Redirect to something new.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_58" = "Take a deep breath and say: 'I release this.' Then physically release—open your hands, drop your shoulders, soften your face. Let go in body and mind.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_59" = "Imperfection isn't a flaw in the system—it IS the system. Everything in nature is imperfect and yet complete. You, and your work, are the same.";
"nudge_obsessive_detail_60" = "You've given this your best effort. Your best is enough. Not perfect, not flawless—enough. Accept that. Celebrate it. Move forward.";

// MARK: - Nudge Expansion v1.8.0 — loneliness (15-60)
"nudge_loneliness_notification_15" = "Send a text. Just one.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_16" = "You're not as alone as you feel.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_17" = "Connection starts with reaching out.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_18" = "Someone is thinking about you right now.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_19" = "Smile at a stranger today.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_20" = "Loneliness lies about your worth.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_21" = "Call someone. Even for 2 minutes.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_22" = "Being alone isn't the same as being lonely.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_23" = "Go where people are.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_24" = "Vulnerability creates connection.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_25" = "You don't need a crowd. Just one person.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_26" = "Ask someone how they're doing. Mean it.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_27" = "Join something. Anything.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_28" = "Your company is valuable. Believe it.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_29" = "Isolation is a habit. Connection is too.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_30" = "Text an old friend. They miss you.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_31" = "Go to a coffee shop. Sit near people.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_32" = "Helping others cures loneliness.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_33" = "You belong here.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_34" = "Not everyone will get you. Someone will.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_35" = "Show up. Even when it's hard.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_36" = "Be the friend you wish you had.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_37" = "Social media isn't connection. Seek the real thing.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_38" = "One meaningful conversation > 100 likes.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_39" = "Your presence matters to someone.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_40" = "Invite someone for coffee.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_41" = "Shared experiences build bonds.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_42" = "It's okay to need people.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_43" = "Walk outside. The world is full of people.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_44" = "Reconnect with someone you've lost touch with.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_45" = "Pets count. Hug yours.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_46" = "Write a letter. To anyone.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_47" = "Community starts with one conversation.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_48" = "You don't have to be interesting. Just be interested.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_49" = "Dance, even alone. Joy attracts company.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_50" = "Say hi to your neighbor.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_51" = "Online communities count. Find your people.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_52" = "You are worthy of connection.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_53" = "The first step is the hardest. Take it.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_54" = "Share a meal with someone.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_55" = "Loneliness is temporary. Connection is one text away.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_56" = "Everyone feels lonely sometimes. You're not broken.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_57" = "Do something for someone else today.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_58" = "Eye contact is a small, powerful connection.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_59" = "You matter. Don't forget that.";
"nudge_loneliness_notification_60" = "Reach out. Someone will be glad you did.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_15" = "Pick up your phone and text one person right now. It can be simple: 'Hey, thinking of you.' That's it. One text can start a conversation that changes your day.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_16" = "Loneliness distorts perception—it makes you feel invisible and unwanted. But people care about you more than you realize. The feeling isn't the fact.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_17" = "Nobody's going to knock on your door and fix your loneliness. Connection requires initiative. Send the first message, make the first call. Start the chain.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_18" = "Right now, someone somewhere is remembering a conversation with you, a laugh you shared, or a kind thing you did. You occupy space in people's minds. You matter.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_19" = "A smile at a stranger is a micro-connection. It costs nothing but changes two people's brain chemistry. Oxytocin releases with even brief positive interactions. Smile.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_20" = "Loneliness whispers that you're unlovable, that nobody cares, that you don't fit. Those are lies. Loneliness is a feeling, not a verdict. Don't believe it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_21" = "A 2-minute phone call can shift your entire day. Call someone you trust—a friend, family member, anyone. Hearing a human voice breaks the isolation spell.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_22" = "Solitude is chosen and restorative. Loneliness is unchosen and painful. If you're lonely, you need connection—not more time alone. Seek people.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_23" = "Go to a park, a café, a library, or a grocery store. Being near other humans—even without talking—reduces loneliness. Proximity is the first step.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_24" = "Deep connection requires vulnerability. Share something real with someone. 'I've been feeling lonely lately.' That honesty opens doors that small talk never will.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_25" = "You don't need a social circle of 50. One genuine connection is enough. One person who really knows you is worth more than a hundred acquaintances.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_26" = "Asking 'How are you?' and genuinely listening creates instant connection. People are desperate to be heard. Be the listener. Connection flows both ways.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_27" = "Join a class, a club, a group, a team—anything with regular meetups. Repeated exposure to the same people is how friendships form. Show up consistently.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_28" = "You have value. Your perspective, your humor, your presence—they contribute to other people's lives in ways you don't see. You're more valued than you know.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_29" = "Isolation becomes comfortable over time—familiar, predictable, safe. But it's a shrinking comfort zone. Start small: one text, one coffee, one hello. Rebuild.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_30" = "Text an old friend you haven't spoken to in months. Say: 'I was thinking about you.' They'll likely respond warmly. Most people love hearing from old friends.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_31" = "You don't have to talk to anyone. Just go sit in a coffee shop where other humans exist. Read a book. The ambient connection of shared space helps. Try it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_32" = "Volunteering, helping a neighbor, buying someone's coffee—acts of kindness create connection while shifting focus from your loneliness to someone else's need.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_33" = "You belong here—on this planet, in this community, in this moment. Your existence isn't an accident. You're part of something larger, even when it doesn't feel like it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_34" = "Not every person will understand you, and that's fine. Your people are out there. Keep showing up, keep being yourself, and you'll find each other.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_35" = "Showing up is 90% of building relationships. Go to the gathering, attend the class, join the call—even when you don't feel like it. Especially then.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_36" = "Be the kind of friend you wish you had: reach out first, listen deeply, show up consistently, and be honest. Model the friendship you want to receive.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_37" = "Scrolling through social media increases loneliness—it shows curated highlights and skips the messy, real parts. Put the phone down. Seek face-to-face time.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_38" = "One real conversation where someone truly listens to you does more for your wellbeing than 100 social media interactions. Quality over quantity. Seek depth.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_39" = "You make a difference in someone's life—even if they haven't told you. Your presence, your kindness, your existence has rippled outward in ways you can't see.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_40" = "Invite someone for coffee this week. Just one person. The worst they can say is no, and the best case is a meaningful conversation. The risk is worth it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_41" = "Doing something together builds bonds faster than talking. Cook with someone, walk together, play a game. Shared activities create shared memories.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_42" = "It's okay to need people. Humans are social animals—we're wired for connection. Needing others isn't weakness. It's being human. Honor that need.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_43" = "Step outside your door. Walk around your neighborhood. Make eye contact with someone. Say hi. These micro-interactions add up and make the world feel less empty.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_44" = "Think of someone you've drifted from. Send them a message: 'I miss our conversations.' Most reconnections start with one brave message. Send it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_45" = "If you have a pet, hold them right now. Physical contact—even with animals—releases oxytocin and reduces loneliness. Connection comes in many forms.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_46" = "Write a letter, an email, or a long text to someone. Pour out what you're feeling. You don't even have to send it—but the act of expressing helps.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_47" = "Community doesn't appear overnight. It's built one conversation at a time. Start today: one person, one genuine exchange. That's the foundation.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_48" = "You don't have to be the most interesting person in the room. Just be genuinely interested in others. Ask questions. Listen. People connect with those who care.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_49" = "Put on music and dance, even alone. Joy is magnetic. When you cultivate joy by yourself, you naturally attract people who want to share in it.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_50" = "Wave to your neighbor. Compliment the barista. Chat with the person in line. These tiny social interactions are the seeds of bigger connections.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_51" = "Online communities built around shared interests can provide genuine connection. Find a forum, a Discord, a group about something you love. Your people are there.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_52" = "You are worthy of deep, meaningful connection. Not because of what you do, but because of who you are. Let people in. They want to know the real you.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_53" = "The first step toward connection is always the hardest. But once you take it—send the text, make the call, show up—everything gets easier. Take the first step now.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_54" = "Sharing a meal is one of the oldest forms of human bonding. Invite someone to eat with you—at home, at a restaurant, even a quick lunch. Food brings people together.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_55" = "Loneliness feels permanent but it's situational. One text, one call, one meetup can transform your entire day. Connection is closer than you think.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_56" = "Everyone feels lonely sometimes—the extroverts, the popular ones, the people who seem to have it all. You're not uniquely broken. You're universally human.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_57" = "Helping someone shifts your focus from your own pain to their need. It creates connection and purpose simultaneously. Find someone to help today.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_58" = "Next time you're in a store or elevator, make eye contact and smile. That 2-second connection activates mirror neurons and creates a tiny moment of shared humanity.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_59" = "You matter. To someone you know, to someone you helped once, to someone watching from a distance. Your existence impacts more lives than you realize.";
"nudge_loneliness_detail_60" = "Reach out to someone right now. Don't overthink the message—just send it. 'Hey, want to hang out?' 'I miss you.' 'How are you?' Someone will be glad you did.";
